    <text id="R11218891T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Confederate Military Secretary A. L. Long writes General Richard Ewell. He
                    mentions General Thomas J. Jackson's May 15, 1862, return to Staunton, VA.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    HDQRS.
                    <name type="recipient">Gen. R. S. EWELL,<lb/> Cmdg. Forces Swift Run Gap:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1862-05-15">May 15, 1862.<lb/> (Received May 17, 2.55 p. m.)</date>
                        <name type="place">Richmond, Va.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>GEN.:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am directed by Gen. Lee to inform you that you need not feel any further
                    solicitude on account of Gen. Jackson, he having been informed by telegram that
                    he is returning to Staunton, and is probably there by this time.</p>
                <p>Gen. Johnston has sent instructions to Gen. Jackson, of which you are doubtless
                    aware. The general thinks that if upon the junction of yours and Gen. Jackson's
                    forces a blow could be struck at Banks, it would make a happy diversion in our
                    favor in other directions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am, general, respectfully, your obedient servant,</salute>
                    <signed>A. L. LONG,<lb/> Col., Military Secretary.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
